{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520025"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:19:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:19:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13133"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13133"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.09,0.15,0.42,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5570"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108102"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5570"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90512"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"2145"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49901"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108102"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is injured via a needle stick whilst drawing blood from a patient with chronic hepatitis B. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe medical student completed his hepatitis B vaccination schedule seven years ago. Serology performed 6 months after his last hepatitis B vaccine was positive for anti-hepatitis B surface antibodies (HBsAbs) with a titre of over 10 mIU/mL.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management of the medical student?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis B immunoglobulin administration","Serologic testing for HBsAg in the source patient","Hepatitis B vaccination booster dose","Reassurance and no further hepatitis B management","Repeat hepatitis B serology in six weeks"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe medical student demonstrates immunity to hepatitis B (positive for HBsAb) with a sufficient titre to provide protection against hepatitis B infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E is therefore appropriate, with no need for further intervention in the medical student, provided other blood-borne viruses have been excluded in the source patient. Hepatitis B vaccination confers immunity by stimulating the development of anti-hepatitis B surface antibodies (HBsAb) against the recombinant hepatitis B surface antigen. Individuals at greater risk of hepatitis B exposure, including healthcare workers and close contacts of known hepatitis B cases, should undergo post-vaccination testing to confirm an effective response to vaccination, indicated by an antibody titre of 10 mIU/mL or more.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E administration would be applicable if the medical student\u0027s hepatitis B vaccination history was unknown or they were not known to be immune. In such cases, administering HBIG provides immediate passive immunity against hepatitis B. It contains high levels of antibodies against hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) and can provide temporary protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerologic testing for HBsAg in the source patient\u003C/strong\u003E involves testing the source patient for HBsAg, which is a marker of active hepatitis B infection. This is not necessary since we already know the patient has chronic hepatitis B. However, the source patient should undergo a risk assessment and testing to determine whether they have hepatitis C or HIV infection, which can also be transmitted through needlestick injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B vaccination booster dose\u003C/strong\u003E for the medical student would be relevant if the medical student\u0027s hepatitis B vaccination history was unknown, incomplete or ineffective. However, in this case, it is not necessary as the medical student has already received the complete hepatitis B vaccination series and has demonstrated adequate antibody levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat hepatitis B serology in six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary in this case. Given that the medical student completed the vaccination series and showed an adequate immune response, there is no need for repeat testing. Further serological monitoring may be necessary if the medical student did not have confirmed hepatitis B immunity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["No further hepatitis B management is required for healthcare workers with documented hepatitis B immunity after a needlestick injury from a hepatitis B positive source."],"references":["Conners EE, Panagiotakopoulos L, Hofmeister MG, Spradling PR, Hagan LM, Harris AM, Rogers-Brown JS, Wester C, Nelson NP; Contributors. Screening and Testing for Hepatitis B Virus Infection: CDC Recommendations - United States, 2023. MMWR Recomm Rep. 2023 Mar 10;72(1):1-25. doi: 10.15585/mmwr.rr7201a1. PMID: 36893044; PMCID: PMC9997714.","Riddell A, Kennedy I, Tong CY. Management of sharps injuries in the health care setting. BMJ. 2015 Jul 29;351:h3733.","NSW Health. HIV, Hepatitis B and Hepatitis C \u2013 Management of Health Care Workers Potentially Exposed. 2022. Available at: https://www1.health.nsw.gov.au/pds/activepdsdocuments/pd2017_010.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90512"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13133"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90512"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T20:42:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T12:22:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5570"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108102"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medica